cat(paste0("In contrast to the strongly arm-dependent `PregEarly -> MatBirth` vaccination step, transfer ",
  "is governed by the Fc\u2013FcRn interaction rather than by which vaccine the mother received; the per-arm ",
  "tables and Figure A1 above let you confirm the subclass hierarchy holds the same way in both arms.\n\n"))
```

## Scale and comparability

Both `MatBirth` and `CordBlood` subclass values are normalized bead-array values on a common
scale, and total IgG comes from a separate ELISA path. Agreement between the total-IgG and IgG1
transfer signals, together with a clean subclass ordering, argues the pattern is biological
rather than a scaling artifact. Note that any feature measured at only one of the two visits
(e.g. a whole-cell readout present at cord but not at maternal birth) contributes no paired
data and does not enter this comparison (see Table 1).

## What would confirm or refine this interpretation

- **Compute explicit cord:maternal ratios per subclass** and compare against published transfer
  ratios; the Δ values here are log10 differences and should line up with that literature.
- **Relate transfer efficiency to gestational age at birth and to maternal titre.** Transfer
  rises with gestational age and can saturate at very high maternal titres; both modulate the
  cord:maternal ratio, especially for the boosted pertussis IgG1.
- **Read Tables 7–8 and Figure A1** to confirm the transfer hierarchy is the same in both arms,
  rather than relying on the pooled medians alone.

